JD 7:

CORE WORK ACTIVITIES  

Act as a strategic procurement partner for IT and Digital disciplines, advising on IT category management, sourcing strategy, technology risk, and compliance requirements. 
Develop and refine category strategies for key IT categories (software, cloud services, hardware, telecom, network services, cybersecurity, IT consulting), ensuring alignment with IT leadership, technology roadmaps, and enterprise objectives. 
Monitor IT demand patterns, spend analytics, technology cost benchmarks, industry trends, and vendor landscapes to identify opportunities, competitive dynamics, and cost-optimization strategies. 
Identify and implement strategies to mitigate IT supply-chain risks—including cybersecurity exposure, data privacy compliance, vendor concentration risk, EOL/EOS challenges, and service-level performance risks. 
Manage and optimize IT supplier relationships, ensuring quality, security, operational continuity, and optimal cost-effectiveness. 
Recommend new IT sourcing strategies, supplier partnerships, demand-management approaches, and process improvements to enhance technology procurement efficiency. 
Lead end-to-end sourcing events for IT initiatives, including requirements gathering, RFP/RFI development, negotiations, and contracting. 
Develop timelines and structure cross-functional IT and procurement teams to implement sourcing strategies and large-scale technology initiatives. 
Use internal tracking tools and KPIs to monitor sourcing progress, competitive bidding, supplier performance, software license utilization, and contract compliance. 
Apply strong analytical and communication skills to evaluate complex IT proposals, score vendor responses, build detailed business cases (including TCO and ROI models), and present recommendations to IT and executive leadership. 
Drive compliance with global IT procurement policies, cybersecurity and privacy standards, and supplier governance frameworks. 
Maintain consistent governance for IT supplier onboarding 
Collaborate with cross-functional stakeholders across IT, cybersecurity, finance, legal, and global operations to ensure procurement initiatives support enterprise goals and objectives.   
Support corporate sustainability, ethical sourcing, and supplier diversity goals within IT supply chains, particularly in hardware lifecycle management and responsible technology sourcing. 

